{
  "answer": "**In Cynewulf's *Juliana*, Saint Juliana is confined to a dungeon (*neorxnawang*, often rendered as \"prison-house\") after torture, where the door is bolted shut in a scene emphasizing her unyielding faith.**[^1]\n\nThe strongest line: \"Then with its bolt, the dungeon door / was barred shut, a work of hammers.\"[^2]\n\n**In *The Wife's Lament* (from the *Old English Elegies* collection), the speaker—a wife exiled due to kin intrigue—is forced to dwell in a natural \"earth-cave\" (*eorðscræfe*) under an oak tree in a wooded grove, a site of endless sorrow and isolation.**[^3]\n\nThe strongest line: \"I was bid to dwell in a wooded grove, / under an oak tree in this earth-cave.\"[^4]\n\n**The framings differ sharply: Juliana's confinement is in a man-made urban dungeon, secured by hammered iron (\"work of hammers\"), yet she remains spiritually triumphant, praising God amid shadows with the Holy Spirit as companion.**[^5] **The Wife's Lament speaker's is a primitive, ancient natural hollow (\"earth-hall\") in a barren, overgrown landscape of dim dales and briars, focused on weeping and unfulfilled longing.**[^6]\n\n**Neither framing leaves room for the other's mode of confinement.** Juliana's explicitly artificial bolt and urban judicial context preclude a tree-shaded earth-cave; the Wife's natural, open grove under an oak (where she walks at dawn) excludes a hammered, locked door.[^7][^8]\n\n[^1]: Cynewulf, *Juliana*, [Chapter 1](/works/cynewulf-juliana-9a2157/01/translation/).\n[^2]: Cynewulf, *Juliana*, [paragraph](/works/cynewulf-juliana-9a2157/01/translation/#p-8666d0).\n[^3]: Unknown, *Old English Elegies*, [Chapter 3](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/03-ik-this-giedd-wreche-bi-me-ful-geomorre/translation/).\n[^4]: Unknown, *Old English Elegies*, [paragraph](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/03-ik-this-giedd-wreche-bi-me-ful-geomorre/translation/#p-c1cc32).\n[^5]: Cynewulf, *Juliana*, [paragraphs](/works/cynewulf-juliana-9a2157/01/translation/#p-89a6c9#p-8666d0).\n[^6]: Unknown, *Old English Elegies*, [paragraph](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/03-ik-this-giedd-wreche-bi-me-ful-geomorre/translation/#p-c1cc32).\n[^7]: Cynewulf, *Juliana*, [paragraph](/works/cynewulf-juliana-9a2157/01/translation/#p-8666d0).\n[^8]: Unknown, *Old English Elegies*, [paragraph](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/03-ik-this-giedd-wreche-bi-me-ful-geomorre/translation/#p-c1cc32).",
